label: ICE makes surprise arrest of immigrant in a Utah courthouse
videoTitle: ICE makes surprise arrest of immigrant in a Utah courthouse
tags: salt lake tribune,utah,salt lake city,immigration,ice,undocumented
videoDescription: A 38-year-old man walked to a microphone in Ogden Justice Court on Jan. 29, expecting a brief hearing where he would be arraigned on misdemeanor charges after a fender bender. He had no idea that U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement officers planned to meet him there. Police said the man had smelled of alcohol after he rear-ended another car, causing minor damage and no injuries, at a stoplight in December. Prosecutors were not seeking a jail sentence. But Judge Clay Stucki broke the news: The man would not be allowed to leave the courthouse — for a reason that had nothing to do with his case. ICE agents were waiting for him. The man took a step back, slowly shook his head and looked toward the ground. ”I personally feel bad that we’re going to have to take you into custody. That isn’t my choice or decision, but it’s something under federal law that I’m going to have to follow,” Stucki said. The man’s wife, seated with his daughter near the back of the room, put her hand to her head. The judge told The Salt Lake Tribune he had not been aware in advance that ICE planned to appear in the courtroom that day. The hearing occurred a week after ICE — in a change from what policy had been under the Biden administration — broadened the circumstances under which it will pursue undocumented immigrants in or near courthouses. Stucki said he worries that any increased ICE enforcement inside courthouses could cause a chilling effect, deterring people from showing up for scheduled court appearances. That could lead to warrants for their arrest or other consequences. “Justice courts certainly are not immigration courts, and none of us right now are probably well acquainted with how immigration law and immigration enforcement fits in, especially with the small misdemeanors that the justice courts handle,” Stucki said. He added that he hopes things work out well for the defendant, who was given the time to enter a plea and resolve his case. The arrest “was, I’m sure, traumatic for him and his family,” Stucki said. “But I do appreciate the ICE agents tried to allow us to make it as least traumatic as possible.” Read more at https://www.sltrib.com/news/2025/02/05/utah-man-unexpectedly-taken-into/ Video from Ogden City Justice Court Reporting by Brock Marchant | The Salt Lake Tribune

label: The dramatic moment ICE grabs Tren de Aragua murder suspect hiding out in Houston
videoTitle: The dramatic moment ICE grabs Tren de Aragua murder suspect hiding out in Houston
tags: breaking news,latest news,new york post,news,ny post,nypost,stories,story,top stories,us news,world news,ice,houston,tren de aragua,ice ride along,houston ice raid,ice raids houston,houston ice raids,texas,migrants,migrant crisis,us migrant crisis,us migrant crisis 2025,tren de aragua ice raid,tren de aragua houston,migrant crisis 2025,texas migrant crisis,caught on camera,caught on video,ice ride along houston,migrant crime,migrant criminals
videoDescription: A Tren de Aragua gangbanger who is wanted for murder in Dallas and holed up in an apartment in Houston got the surprise of his life earlier this month when federal agents swarmed him as part of President Trump’s deportation raids across the US. NY Post reporter Jennie Taer was there with ICE officers as they staked out the alleged killer’s hideout in a crime-ridden neighborhood with a large migrant community. Watch the dramatic scene unfold as officers take the suspect into custody. Federal agents had received a report that the “documented” member of the Venezuelan prison gang was in the area after he was spotted walking his dog. For hours, officers from ICE and a host of other federal agencies waited for the target to show himself again. label: ICE launches raids on illegal migrants in Georgia
videoTitle: ICE launches raids on illegal migrants in Georgia
channelTitle: The Times and The Sunday Times
tags: ICE migrant raids,Donald Trump migration policy,Illegal migrants in USA,ICE raid Illegal migrant,Mexico
videoDescription: U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) agents conducted a targeted operation in the early hours of Wednesday morning (February 5) to apprehend José Miguel Corral-Reyes, an alleged migrant from Mexico with a criminal history. Reuters witnessed the arrest, which took place at a Marathon Gas Station in Rex, Georgia, after agents had staked out the area. Corral-Reyes was quickly surrounded by agents and placed into an unmarked law enforcement vehicle. During the operation, officers said they discovered a firearm in his vehicle and ammunition in his pocket. Kristen Sullivan, the Atlanta Deputy Field Office Director for the U.S. Department of Homeland Security, said Corral-Reyes had previously been arrested on multiple charges including driving under the influence and reckless conduct involving a firearm. An arrest record sent to Reuters showed criminal convictions for Corral-Reyes, including shoplifting, driving under the influence (DUI) and simple assault, dating back to 2002. “In this situation, when he was arrested by the local police and when they interviewed him, he admitted that he was from Mexico,” Sullivan said. videoDescription: Video from the Associated Press shows a dozen immigration agents wearing body armor and armed with handguns as they fanned out into the Silver Spring suburbs to grab their targets. ICE Field Office Director Matthew Elliston says ICE only does targeted operations. “ICE only does targeted enforcement operations. We do not do raids. We do not do dragnets . e do not do sweeps. That is not something ICE has ever done. We do targeted enforcement, but part of that targeted enforcement, if I'm going for an MS-13 gang member and I see someone next to him has a big 13 on their face, I'm going to start asking that person questions,” Elliston said. The group of immigration agents comprehended 12 individuals before noon on Monday, but still did not reach all of their targets.

videoDescription: A taco truck in Memphis, Tennessee, released security footage showing four men in plain clothes approaching the truck and then detaining the employees. videoDescription: A large group of people protesting President Donald Trump's illegal immigration crackdown stormed the 101 Freeway in downtown Los Angeles on Sunday, causing major delays for both sides of traffic in the area, according to police. At one point, the Los Angeles Police Department declared it a "non-permitted demonstration," and advised people to expect traffic delays. The crowd grew to a few thousand people who marched to City Hall, before many walked onto the freeway near the Alameda Street exit shortly after noon. Police reported at 1:19 p.m. that the demonstration had moved back onto surface streets, opening both north and southbound lanes of the freeway. Several minutes later officials said the protesters had moved back onto the freeway. "Please avoid the 101 freeway in DTLA between I-110 and Mission Rd., as we work to remove a protest from the freeway," the CHP said on social media. "Accessing state highways or roads to protest is unlawful and extremely dangerous because it puts protesters, motorists and first responders at great risk of injury." videoDescription: A lot of us are stuck in the middle when it comes to immigration enforcement. I talk about having felt this conflict, how I resolved it, and argue that deportations are not unjust per se. label: ICE Protest Spirals out of Control in City of Glendale in Arizona
videoTitle: ICE Protest Spirals out of Control in City of Glendale in Arizona
tags: news,breaking news,breakingnews,keynewsnetwork,keynews.tv,key news network,los angeles
videoDescription: GLENDALE, Ariz., Feb. 3 (KNN) — Around 5 p.m. Sunday, hundreds of demonstrators gathered at the intersection of 67th Avenue and Camelback Road in Glendale to protest recent American immigration policy changes. Protesters waved flags and signs as passing drivers honked. Eventually, a large box of fireworks was placed and set off in the middle of the intersection. Police formed a riot line and began issuing verbal commands to the protesters to clear the intersection. A firework was then thrown at the officers. Officers began retreating to the north, leaving several patrol cars unattended. Several protesters began damaging the police cars before a person entered and drove off in one police vehicle down the street before fleeing on foot (5:58 on the video timestamp). label: ICE Raids: Fox News reporter witnesses mass deportation efforts
videoTitle: ICE Raids: Fox News reporter witnesses mass deportation efforts
tags: news,united states,politics,ice raids,trump ice raids,trump immigration,trump mass deportations,tom homan,what is ice raid,what is ice,trump ice raid,immigration,ice immigration,immigration raid,boston,boston raid,video ice raids,ice raids video,ice raids ride along,ice raids masschusetts,ice raids long island,ice raid today,fox news,fox news bill melugin,ice boston,donald trump,trump news,trump executive order,trump,president trump,live news
videoDescription: Fox News' Bill Melugin shares key takeaways from his exclusive ride-along with elite ICE officers as they conduct raids in Boston. Fox News embedded exclusively with Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) in Boston as the agency targeted egregious criminal aliens, including MS-13 gang members and murder suspects, as part of mass deportation efforts under President Donald Trump. Fox News witnessed ICE Boston make eight arrests, including multiple MS-13, Interpol Red Notices, murder and rape suspects, and a volatile Haitian gang member with 18 convictions in recent years who told our cameras that he "ain’t going back to Haiti" and "f--- Trump, Biden forever!" label: ICE Conducts Made-for-TV Raids as Cities from Chicago to Newark Resist Trump s Immigration Crackdown
videoTitle: ICE Conducts Made-for-TV Raids as Cities from Chicago to Newark Resist Trump s Immigration Crackdown
tags: Democracy Now,Amy Goodman,News,Politics,democracynow,Independent Media,Breaking News,World News
videoDescription: Support our work: https://democracynow.org/donate/sm-desc-yt Immigration and Customs Enforcement is ramping up raids across the United States, arresting more than 1,000 people in operations Monday after detaining a similar number on Sunday. Immigrant communities and their allies say the raids violate human rights, the Constitution, and are being carried out in retaliation against sanctuary cities that have policies aimed at protecting undocumented residents. In Chicago, immigrant rights organizer Dulce Guzmán says there is "palpable fear and anxiety among families," but she lauds elected officials, including Mayor Brandon Johnson and Governor J.B. Pritzker, for pushing back against what she says is the Trump administration's "white supremacist agenda." Meanwhile, in Newark, New Jersey, Mayor Ras Baraka has condemned an ICE raid last week at a seafood depot where federal agents took three people into custody, including a U.S. military veteran. "Simply being in proximity to their target, which is immigrant communities, is enough to arrest and detain you, too," says Amy Torres, executive director of the New Jersey Alliance for Immigrant Justice. She encourages people to know their rights, such as the ability to record ICE agents and to refuse orders without a warrant. "One of their most effective tools is fear and panic," Torres says. label: INMIGRANTES PARALIZAN WALMART: REDADAS DE ICE DEJAN TIENDAS VACIAS | TheMXFam
videoTitle: INMIGRANTES PARALIZAN WALMART: REDADAS DE ICE DEJAN TIENDAS VACIAS | TheMXFam
tags: walmart,redadas ICE,trump,crisis económica,deportaciones,home depot,costco,estados unidos,inmigración,multimillonarios,blackrock,latinos en eeuu,tiendas vacías,colapso económico,trump 2025,política migratoria,cierre de tiendas,despidos masivos,sanciones económicas,migrantes escondidos,crisis en walmart,trump biden,recesión en eeuu,última hora eeuu,impacto migratorio,redadas masivas,trump news,negocios quebrando
videoDescription: Las redadas de ICE han desatado el caos en las tiendas más grandes de Estados Unidos. Walmart, Costco, Home Depot y otras cadenas están experimentando un fenómeno que nunca antes habían visto: pasillos vacíos, empleados desaparecidos y una crisis que crece cada día. Los inmigrantes, en respuesta al miedo a las detenciones masivas, han dejado sus trabajos y han reducido su presencia en espacios públicos. Y ahora, las mismas empresas que antes apoyaban las políticas de Trump, están rogando que esto pare. La ironía es brutal. Durante años, las grandes corporaciones financiaron discursos contra la migración, pero ahora que se están quedando sin trabajadores ni clientes, están sintiendo el golpe en su bolsillo. ¿Podrá la economía soportar este impacto o estamos viendo el principio de un colapso provocado por el propio gobierno? Los datos son claros: en apenas una semana, ICE ha detenido a miles de personas, los negocios están en crisis y la presión sobre la Casa Blanca no deja de aumentar. En este episodio, analizamos el impacto real de estas redadas, los números que muestran el efecto económico inmediato y las declaraciones de empresarios que, irónicamente, ahora ven en la migración la única forma de salvar sus negocios. ¿Trump podrá sostener esta política o la presión de Wall Street lo obligará a dar marcha atrás?

videoDescription: Jordan Chariton reports on a letter several Democratic lawmakers sent to President Trump requesting that ICE officials stop targeting, detaining, and harassing Native Americans following reports that Native Americans from Navajo Nation and other tribes were detained—in some cases for as many as seven to eight hours—by ICE as part of President Trump's ICE raids across the country. videoDescription: Megyn Kelly is joined by Steve Bannon, host of Bannon's War Room, to discuss the media hoax about ICE raiding a Chicago school, how ICE have actually been arresting criminal illegal immigrants all weekend, the real plan by the Trump administration to fix our immigration crisis, Selena Gomez’s out-of-touch and embarrassing meltdown on social media, ABC host Martha Raddatz trying to spin the deportation stories but failing, JD Vance embarrassing CBS News host Margaret Brennan with facts and rational arguments, Brennan's failed attacks on immigration, Trump’s tariff threat against Colombia over their refusal to take back their citizens who came to America illegally, how the threat immediately got action after the public negotiation, and more. Then Batya Ungar-Sargon, author of "Second Class," joins to discuss CBS host Margaret Brennan's ridiculous question about inflation and grocery prices, Hollywood and media elite still dealing with Trump Derangement Syndrome, Trump’s trip to North Carolina raise awareness for the forgotten victims of Hurricane Helene, his unique ability to promote the people who very rarely get support, Trump bringing common sense to California after the wildfires, his showdown with LA Mayor Karen Bass, and more. label: Texas Teacher Invites ICE to Deport His Students  Regrets it IMMEDIATELY
videoTitle: Texas Teacher Invites ICE to Deport His Students  Regrets it IMMEDIATELY
tags: fox 4,fort worth isd,immigration news,trump,mass deportation,immigration,tom homan,ICE raids,politics,the humanist report
videoDescription: A Texas teacher went viral after calling on ICE to deport his 10th and 11th grade students because he suspected they were undocumented for the fact that they didn’t speak English. ICE didn’t come for his students; but instead, the school district came for him. He was suspended immediately, subjected to an investigation, and will almost certainly be terminated. Meanwhile, his community has shown overwhelming support to immigrants. That support is now being expressed in cities across the country. In fact, pro-immigrant activism has actually made it difficult to carry out mass deportations. Tom Homan, Trump’s Border Czar, said their job has been made more difficult since so many people know their rights. label: ICE arrests are up. So is misinformation around them.
videoTitle: ICE arrests are up. So is misinformation around them.
videoDescription: Immigration arrests have undoubtedly spiked under the new Trump administration, but the scale of the increase is difficult to measure. The crackdown is blurring the lines between reality, rumor and performance — reshaping daily life in immigrant communities, even when enforcement never arrives. ✍️: Jamiles Lartey & 🎥: Chris Vazquez / The Marshall Project Transcript: IMMIGRATION AND CUSTOMS ENFORCEMENT: We’ve arrested thousands of immigrants. CHRIS VAZQUEZ: Really? IMMIGRATION AND CUSTOMS ENFORCEMENT: Yeah, we averaged more than 800 arrests per day during Trump’s first 10 days in office. A NEW YORK TIMES ANALYSIS: That’s more than double the daily average of the last eight years. CHRIS: Yeah, I know immigration arrests have spiked under Trump. IMMIGRATION DATA EXPERTS: But we’re skeptical of how much you say they’ve spiked. You’re releasing information way faster than usual, and leaving out details. Like where these arrests happened or whether the people you arrested are being detained, deported or released. CHRIS 2: And reports of raids are reshaping lives in immigrant communities, even when those reports aren’t true. Like in New Jersey, the owners of a Salvadorian restaurant lost tons of business after a false TikTok about a raid there. CHRIS 1: So false reports and publicity are drumming up fear, but there has been a real increase in enforcement, right? CHRIS 2: Right. And one reason seems to be more “collateral arrests.” NPR JOURNALISTS: This has looked like raids targeting migrants with criminal records while also detaining other people nearby. NBC NEWS JOURNALISTS: On one day in late January, nearly half of the 1,200 migrants arrested didn’t have criminal records. CHRIS 2: So there are reports of immigrants avoiding public spaces because of all this. But not everywhere. TRUMP’S BORDER CZAR: I’m frustrated at how well some immigrants in Chicago have been educated on how to defy and hide from ICE. IMMIGRANT RIGHTS ACTIVISTS: Which we’re proud of.
